Supercell thunderstorms are powerful, long-lived storms characterized by a persistent rotating updraft. These are among the most severe types.
Mesoscale convective systems (MCSs) involve large clusters of storms spanning many miles. They can produce widespread, sustained heavy rainfall.
Squall lines are organized groups of thunderstorms that move rapidly across the landscape. They generate sudden, strong wind gusts.
Tropical thunderstorms form in the tropics and are heavily influenced by warm ocean temperatures. They can sometimes intensify into tropical cyclones.
Flash thunderstorm complexes are fast-moving, intense storms that dissipate quickly. They are often responsible for localized flash flooding.
